      <div class="content-section"><div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Benefits</span><h2>Why Choose ELSS for Tax Saving?</h2></div>
        <ul class="feature-list">
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Shortest Lock-in Among 80C Options</strong><p>ELSS has a 3-year lock-in — the shortest among all Section 80C instruments. PPF locks your money for 15 years, NSC for 5 years, and tax-saving FDs for 5 years. The shorter lock-in means your money is accessible sooner while still earning tax benefits.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Highest Return Potential</strong><p>As equity funds, ELSS has historically delivered 13%–16% returns — roughly double the returns of PPF (7.1%) and tax-saving FDs (6.5%–7%). Over 10 years, ₹1.5 lakh annual ELSS investment at 14% would grow to approximately ₹31 lakh vs ₹22 lakh in PPF at 7.1%.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Save Up to ₹46,800 in Tax</strong><p>Under Section 80C, you can claim deduction up to ₹1.5 lakh per year on ELSS investments. In the 30% tax bracket (including cess), this translates to an actual tax saving of ₹46,800 per year — effectively a guaranteed 31.2% first-year return on your investment.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>SIP for Spread Tax Saving</strong><p>Instead of rushing to invest ₹1.5 lakh in March, spread your ELSS investment via monthly SIP of ₹12,500. SIP ensures disciplined investing throughout the year and benefits from rupee cost averaging in volatile markets.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>No Maximum Investment Limit</strong><p>While tax deduction is capped at ₹1.5 lakh, there is no maximum investment limit. You can invest any amount in ELSS beyond ₹1.5 lakh for its equity growth potential. Only the lock-in applies to each investment unit.</p></div></li>
          <li><i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i><div><strong>Favorable Tax on Gains</strong><p>ELSS gains after the 3-year lock-in are treated as long-term capital gains (LTCG). Gains up to ₹1.25 lakh per year are completely tax-free. Beyond that, LTCG is taxed at just 12.5% — significantly lower than income tax slab rates on FD interest.</p></div></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="content-section"><div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">How to Invest</span><h2>How to Invest in ELSS for Tax Saving</h2></div>
        <div class="steps-grid">
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">1</div><h3>Calculate Tax Saving Need</h3><p>Check your Section 80C utilization from EPF, insurance premiums, and home loan principal. Invest the remaining balance (up to ₹1.5 lakh) in ELSS for maximum tax benefit.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">2</div><h3>Choose Top ELSS Fund</h3><p>Select an ELSS fund with consistent 3–5 year track record. Since ELSS invests across market caps (like a flexi cap fund), choose one that aligns with your risk tolerance and return expectations.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">3</div><h3>Start Monthly SIP</h3><p>Set up SIP of ₹12,500/month to spread your ₹1.5 lakh investment over the year. This is better than investing a lump sum in March, as you benefit from rupee cost averaging and avoid timing risk.</p></div>
          <div class="step-card"><div class="step-num">4</div><h3>Continue Beyond Lock-in</h3><p>After the 3-year lock-in, don't rush to redeem. ELSS performs best over 5–10 years. Continue holding for long-term wealth creation. Each SIP installment has its own 3-year lock-in period.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
