  <section class="faq-section"><div class="container">
    <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">FAQs</span><h2>Frequently Asked Questions About ELSS Funds</h2></div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is ELSS better than PPF for tax saving?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>For investors who can accept market risk and have a 5+ year horizon, ELSS is superior to PPF. ELSS offers higher returns (13%–16% vs 7.1%), shorter lock-in (3 years vs 15 years), and equity market exposure. PPF is better for risk-averse investors who need guaranteed, fixed returns with sovereign safety. An ideal strategy is to split your 80C allocation between both — ELSS for growth and PPF for safety.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>What happens after the 3-year lock-in period?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>After 3 years, your ELSS units become fully redeemable. You can sell them at the prevailing NAV on any business day. However, there's no compulsion to redeem — you can continue holding for as long as you want. Financial advisors recommend holding ELSS for 5–10 years for optimal returns. Each SIP installment has its own 3-year lock-in, so monthly SIPs unlock gradually.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Can I invest more than ₹1.5 lakh in ELSS?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Yes, there is no maximum investment limit for ELSS. However, the Section 80C tax deduction is capped at ₹1.5 lakh per financial year. Any amount invested beyond ₹1.5 lakh will not provide additional tax benefits but will still enjoy equity growth and the 3-year lock-in applies to all units. If you want to invest more in equity without lock-in, consider regular mutual funds instead.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>Is ELSS SIP or lump sum better for tax saving?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Monthly SIP of ₹12,500 is generally recommended over a one-time lump sum in March. SIP spreads your investment across the year, benefiting from rupee cost averaging and reducing the risk of investing at market highs. It also ensures you don't procrastinate on tax planning. The total annual SIP of ₹1,50,000 (₹12,500 x 12) fully utilizes the 80C limit.</p></div></div></div>
      <div class="faq-item"><div class="faq-question"><span>How are ELSS gains taxed after redemption?</span><i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></div><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner"><p>Since ELSS has a mandatory 3-year lock-in, all gains are classified as Long-Term Capital Gains (LTCG). LTCG up to ₹1.25 lakh per financial year is completely tax-free. Gains exceeding ₹1.25 lakh are taxed at 12.5% without indexation benefit. This is far more favorable than FD interest which is taxed at your full slab rate (up to 30%).</p></div></div></div>
    </div>
